-- ── Genealogy ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Genealogy is a free, open-source, Laravel-built web application for recording family members, relationships, and multi-tree family history research.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, NY, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Dutch$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Mandarin$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Genealogy (kreaweb) Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Genealogy is a free, open-source Laravel family tree app for recording relationships and ancestry. See its features, licensing, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Genealogy, hosted at genealogy.kreaweb.be, is a free and open-source family tree web application built with the Laravel PHP framework. It is developed and maintained by KREAWEB, a web development studio credited on GitHub under the account MGeurts, with the underlying code published as an MIT-licensed repository named 'genealogy'. Public documentation about the project describes it as evolving alongside successive Laravel releases, with KREAWEB's own blog referencing a 'Laravel 11 - Genealogy' build and the GitHub repository description referencing Laravel 13, indicating the project is actively kept current with the Laravel ecosystem rather than being a static, abandoned codebase. Unlike large commercial genealogy platforms that charge subscriptions for access to historical records and DNA matching, Genealogy is explicitly positioned as free to use for non-commercial purposes, targeting individual family history researchers and hobbyists rather than professional genealogists or commercial data brokers. The application's core feature set centers on structured family record-keeping: users create accounts, then build out family trees by recording individuals, their partnerships (including explicit support for same-sex couples), and their children, establishing a relational family structure that can be browsed and explored. A distinguishing organizational feature is its support for teams, where a family tree can be owned by a team of collaborators rather than a single user, and different teams can be created for different family trees, which is useful for research projects that involve multiple contributing relatives or collaborators working on the same lineage. To help prospective users understand the tool without creating an account or entering real family data, the live site includes two public demonstration family trees: one modeling the British Royal Family and another modeling the Kennedy family, both well-documented public lineages that make it easy to see how the tool renders multi-generational relationships, marriages, and children in practice. On the data portability front, the project has been actively building GEDCOM import and export capability, the same open interchange standard used across the genealogy software industry (including by Ancestry, MyHeritage, and FamilySearch), with initial import/export capabilities already functional and further development ongoing at the time of research; this signals an intent to let users move family tree data in and out of the platform rather than lock it in permanently. Because Genealogy is a self-hosted-friendly, open-source Laravel application rather than a funded startup product, there is no publicly disclosed founding year, employee count, or funding history in the way there would be for a venture-backed company; what public information exists points to KREAWEB, credited in project materials as based in New York, NY, as the studio behind its design and development, with the GitHub user MGeurts serving as the primary listed developer and maintainer. The MIT license under which the code is distributed means any developer can inspect, self-host, fork, or extend the application for their own use, which is a meaningful differentiator from closed, proprietary genealogy SaaS platforms. In terms of competitive positioning, Genealogy competes less with giants like Ancestry or MyHeritage, which differentiate primarily through massive proprietary historical record archives and DNA testing services, and more with other lightweight, self-hostable or free genealogy tools such as Gramps, GeneWeb, and Genea.app (also covered separately in this directory), all of which appeal to users who want direct control over their family data without a subscription. Genealogy's particular niche within that smaller open-source category is its modern web-app UX built on Laravel, its explicit multi-user 'team' collaboration model for shared family trees, and its support for inclusive family structures such as same-sex couples, which is not always a given in older or more traditionally structured genealogy software. Because the software's language support spans at least eleven languages according to the project's own materials, it is clearly designed with an international, non-English-first user base in mind, which is somewhat unusual for a small independently maintained open-source project and suggests either community-contributed translations or deliberate internationalization work by the KREAWEB team. Overall, Genealogy is best understood as a modern, actively developed, free, and mission-driven alternative to paid genealogy platforms for users who want a straightforward, web-based way to record and browse family relationships without financial cost or vendor lock-in, at the tradeoff of not offering the historical record databases, DNA matching, or large-scale hint systems that define the commercial genealogy category.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '9a671332-0a6d-44a2-a483-911ca563acab';

