-- ── Geneva ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Geneva is a free, all-in-one group communication app combining chat, audio rooms, livestreaming, forums, and event planning for clubs and communities, now owned by Bumble Inc.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, NY, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Geneva Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Geneva is a free group chat and community app with rooms, livestreaming, and event planning. See features, pricing, and top Geneva alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Geneva is a free, all-in-one communication app designed for groups, clubs, and communities rather than enterprise workplace teams, positioning itself with the tagline 'the online place to find your offline people.' The company was founded in 2018 by Justin Hauser, who is also known as a co-founder of the CBD beverage company Recess, and is headquartered in New York City. Over its lifetime as an independent company, Geneva raised outside funding reported at roughly $26.5 million across three rounds from four investors, according to Crunchbase-style aggregator data, before reaching a significant milestone in its corporate history: the company was acquired by Bumble Inc., the publicly traded parent company of the Bumble dating app, in a deal that closed on July 1, 2024. Following the acquisition, Geneva has continued to operate as a distinct product and brand under Bumble's ownership rather than being immediately folded into or discontinued in favor of Bumble's core dating product, and Geneva's own marketing has publicly celebrated becoming part of Bumble Inc. Functionally, Geneva differentiates itself from both traditional group chat apps like Discord and workplace tools like Slack by focusing on real-world, local community building: the product's core use case is helping people who already share an interest, whether a book club, a running group, a professional network, or a hobbyist community, coordinate both online conversation and offline, in-person meetups and events. The app's feature set is built around multiple distinct 'room' types that a group can mix and match depending on its needs. Chat rooms provide full-featured text messaging with @mentions, threaded replies, emoji reactions, GIFs, file attachments, polls, message pinning, and typing indicators, covering the baseline expectations of a modern group chat product. Audio rooms let members hang out in live voice conversations, similar in spirit to Discord voice channels or Clubhouse-style audio spaces. Forum rooms support longer-form, threaded discussion better suited to in-depth topics than a fast-scrolling chat feed. Broadcast rooms allow a group to livestream events, tutorials, or gatherings such as virtual dance parties to an audience, with up to nine people able to appear live on-air simultaneously while thousands of viewers can tune in to watch, giving Geneva a lightweight built-in live video broadcasting capability. Video rooms round out the real-time communication options, supporting group video calls with up to sixteen simultaneous participants. On top of these communication surfaces, Geneva includes organizational tooling aimed specifically at community management: group administrators can screen prospective members using custom questionnaires before granting access, plan events with built-in invitation flows and a centralized shared calendar, assign customizable roles and permissions to different members, and, notably, support token-gating, a feature that restricts access to a community based on ownership of a specific blockchain token or NFT, which reflects a period during Geneva's development when web3 and token-gated communities were a notable growth category for consumer social apps. Geneva is available as a free app across iPhone, Android, and the web, with no disclosed premium subscription tier for end users in current public materials, which is consistent with a consumer social product monetized more likely through data, partnerships, or its parent company's broader business model post-acquisition rather than direct subscription revenue from community members. The platform has also attracted attention beyond hobbyist and social communities: trade press coverage has noted that beauty brands have used Geneva alongside Slack for private group messaging with customers and fans, indicating some adoption by consumer brands seeking a more intimate, community-style channel than public social media. In the competitive landscape, Geneva sits between Discord, which dominates gaming and hobbyist communities with similar chat, voice, and now video capabilities but skews toward a younger, gaming-native audience, and platforms like Mighty Networks or Circle, which target creators and course communities with more emphasis on monetization and content libraries than live audio/video interaction. Geneva's specific differentiation is its emphasis on connecting online community activity to real-world, local, in-person events ('the people you want to meet and the things you want to do in your city'), its inclusive positioning toward LGBTQIA+ communities, and its combination of chat, audio, video, forum, and broadcast room types within a single, unified group rather than requiring separate apps or channels for each communication mode. Its acquisition by Bumble Inc. in 2024 also signals a strategic bet by Bumble to expand beyond one-to-one dating matches into broader social and community-based connection, potentially integrating Geneva's group and community infrastructure with Bumble's existing user base and relationship-focused brand over time, though the two products continue to operate under separate branding as of the most recent publicly available information.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'f060f9b6-0029-44ee-a1ce-f641464783dd';

