-- ── GeneWeb ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$GeneWeb is a free, open-source genealogy software engine written in OCaml, offering a web interface for building, browsing, and analyzing large genealogical databases, used by projects like Roglo.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1998, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Dutch$q$, $q$Danish$q$, $q$Finnish$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Swedish$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$GeneWeb Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$GeneWeb is a free, open-source OCaml genealogy engine with a web interface. Explore its features, licensing, technical architecture, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$GeneWeb is a free, open-source genealogy software engine created by Daniel de Rauglaudre, a researcher at Inria (Institut national de recherche en informatique et en automatique), the French national computer science research institute. GeneWeb was written in OCaml, a functional programming language also developed within Inria's research community, and the project has been active since 1998, making it one of the longest-running open-source genealogy platforms still maintained today. The software is distributed under the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPL-2.0), and its source code is maintained on GitHub under the geneweb organization, where the project has accumulated 386 stars and 115 forks at the time of research, with its most recent tracked release being version 7.1.0-beta2. Architecturally, GeneWeb is fundamentally different from typical desktop genealogy software: rather than being a standalone application with its own file browser and print layouts, GeneWeb operates as a lightweight embedded web server that can host and serve any number of genealogical databases simultaneously, dynamically generating HTML pages in response to queries, and viewable through any standard web browser, including Chrome, Firefox, and other modern browsers. This means a single GeneWeb installation can be run entirely offline on a personal computer for private research, or deployed on a remote server (via a background daemon process or through the CGI protocol) to make a family tree browsable over the internet to relatives or the public, which is a major reason the software became the technical foundation for some of the largest publicly accessible genealogical databases in the world. The most prominent example is Roglo, a public genealogy database built on GeneWeb containing more than 8.5 million individuals (with some references citing figures beyond 11 million as the database has continued to grow), demonstrating that the underlying engine can scale to very large, heavily cross-referenced datasets while remaining performant. On the data model and feature side, GeneWeb includes an efficient relationship and consanguinity rate calculator, letting researchers determine how closely related any two people in a database are and compute inbreeding coefficients, a computationally nontrivial feature that reflects the software's academic research origins. It generates a range of built-in statistics automatically from a loaded database, including lists of the oldest living individuals, recently recorded weddings or deaths, and age pyramids for a given year, useful for demographic analysis of large family datasets rather than just individual tree browsing. The software supports rich, wikitext-style formatting in notes attached to individuals and families, including internal cross-references between people and embedded media, giving researchers a way to attach sourced narrative context to bare genealogical facts. For data interchange, GeneWeb supports both its own native 'GW' text-based database format, optimized for its own storage and query engine, and the industry-standard GEDCOM format used by virtually every other genealogy tool, including commercial platforms like Ancestry, MyHeritage, and FamilySearch, meaning researchers can import existing family trees into GeneWeb or export GeneWeb data for use elsewhere. Administration is handled through a dedicated utility called gwsetup, which provides a browser-based interface for configuring and maintaining GeneWeb installations and databases without requiring command-line expertise for routine tasks, lowering the barrier to entry for non-technical genealogists once the software itself has been installed. GeneWeb runs on Unix, Linux, Microsoft Windows, and macOS, and its interface has been localized into at least nine languages (Danish, Dutch, English, Finnish, French, German, Italian, Spanish, and Swedish), reflecting adoption across multiple European genealogy communities beyond its French origin. Within the genealogy software landscape, GeneWeb's closest comparisons are other open-source, self-hosted genealogy engines such as Gramps (a desktop-first application with a plugin ecosystem) and, within this directory, the similarly named but functionally distinct web app Genealogy (a Laravel-based tool) and Genea.app (a serverless, browser-only GEDCOM editor); GeneWeb differs from both by being explicitly designed as a server application capable of hosting very large, multi-million-person public databases with statistical and demographic analysis tools rather than acting as a lightweight personal tree editor. Because GeneWeb has no corporate backing, there is no publicly documented company size, headquarters, or revenue; it exists purely as a community-and-academic-maintained open-source project, with ongoing development now supported by a collaborative group of contributors and translators beyond its original creator, and its long operational history combined with its role powering large-scale public genealogical databases like Roglo represents its primary claim to significance in the genealogy software space.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'eed15499-677d-4aec-b709-b24744a436e5';

