-- ── Gerbera ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Gerbera is a free, open-source UPnP media server written in C++ that streams music, video, and photos to UPnP and DLNA-compatible devices on a home network.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2016, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Gerbera Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Gerbera is a free, open-source UPnP and DLNA media server for streaming music, video, and photos across your home network. See features and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Gerbera is a free, open-source UPnP media server designed to stream digital media, including music, video, and photos, across a home network to any UPnP-compliant device, such as smart TVs, game consoles, and dedicated media players. The project began in 2016 as a fork of MediaTomb, an earlier UPnP media server whose upstream development had stalled; Gerbera's own project description explicitly credits this lineage, describing itself as being 'proudly built upon MediaTomb 0.12.1, continuing that project's great legacy.' The software is licensed under the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2), with copyright notices spanning from the original MediaTomb developers (2005-2008) through current Gerbera contributors (2016-2025), reflecting nearly two decades of combined development history across both projects. As of the most recent data gathered for this profile, the Gerbera GitHub repository has accumulated 1,400 stars and 223 forks, with 41 tagged releases, the most recent being version 3.2.1 released in March 2026, indicating an actively maintained project with a regular release cadence rather than an abandoned or dormant fork. Technically, Gerbera is written primarily in C++ (accounting for roughly 74.5% of the codebase), with JavaScript making up about 14.5% (used for server-side scripting of import and transcoding logic) and CMake used for its build system. Its core dependencies include libupnp or the alternative libnpupnp library for implementing the UPnP protocol itself, pugixml for XML parsing, jsoncpp for JSON handling, and SQLite3 as its embedded database engine for storing media metadata; optional dependencies extend its capabilities further, including FFmpeg and TagLib for deeper media metadata extraction and thumbnail generation, and the Duktape JavaScript engine for enabling custom, script-based import and transcoding rules. Functionally, Gerbera provides a browser-based Web UI that presents both a tree view of its internal media database and a view of the underlying file system, letting users add, remove, edit, and browse media alongside its extracted metadata. It automatically extracts metadata from a wide range of audio and image formats, including MP3, OGG, AAC, M4A, FLAC, WavPack, and JPG among others, and can generate thumbnails for supported media types. For devices or media formats that cannot be played natively, Gerbera supports flexible transcoding through configurable plugins or external scripts, converting media into a format compatible with the requesting device on the fly. Additional features include automatic rescanning of watched directories so newly added media is detected without manual intervention, Last.fm scrobbling support for tracking listening history, and the ability to include external URLs (such as internet radio streams) as browsable media items alongside local files. Gerbera runs on Linux, BSD, and macOS, and has been compiled for a wide range of processor architectures beyond typical x86 desktops, including ARM and MIPS, which makes it a popular choice for self-hosters running it on low-power hardware such as Raspberry Pi devices, NAS units, or router-class hardware, in addition to full desktop and server Linux installations. It is worth noting, based on the project's own documentation, that Gerbera is technically a UPnP media server rather than a certified DLNA server, though it provides partial DLNA compatibility that works with many, though not necessarily all, DLNA-certified client devices; this distinction matters for users pairing Gerbera with picky smart TVs or DLNA-only hardware, where some troubleshooting or configuration adjustment may be required. Within the self-hosted and home-lab software ecosystem, Gerbera is most directly comparable to other open-source UPnP/DLNA servers such as MiniDLNA (ReadyMedia), Universal Media Server, and Serviio, as well as more full-featured self-hosted media platforms like Plex, Jellyfin, and Emby, which add features such as user accounts, remote access, and richer client apps beyond the core streaming protocol. Gerbera's particular niche is being a lightweight, protocol-focused, highly configurable UPnP server well suited to users who specifically need broad UPnP/DLNA device compatibility (for older smart TVs, UPnP-capable audio receivers, or games consoles) without the heavier resource footprint or account-based architecture of a platform like Plex or Jellyfin, and its packaging for a wide range of CPU architectures makes it a common choice for router firmware distributions and low-power NAS appliances specifically because of that lightweight footprint.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '1fd3a23c-84e4-4c6b-bd89-e880123d495c';

