-- ── getleon ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Leon is a free, open-source, self-hosted personal AI assistant supporting voice and text interaction, agentic task execution, and extensible custom skills.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2017, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Leon AI (getleon.ai) Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Leon is a free, open-source personal AI assistant you can self-host. Explore its voice/text features, skills system, architecture, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Leon, marketed at getleon.ai and developed in the open on GitHub under the leon-ai organization, is a free, open-source personal AI assistant designed to run on a user's own server rather than relying on a closed, cloud-only commercial voice assistant like Alexa, Google Assistant, or Siri. The project traces its origin to 2017 and has been actively developed since 2019, created by developer Louis Grenard, known publicly as grenlouis. Released under the permissive MIT License, Leon has grown into one of the more prominent open-source personal assistant projects on GitHub, currently showing approximately 17,400 stars, 1,500 forks, and 276 watchers, a scale of community interest that places it well ahead of most niche self-hosted assistant projects, and the project has attracted institutional sponsorship from OpenAI, JetBrains, and MacStadium, lending it additional credibility and infrastructure support beyond pure volunteer contribution. Leon's core value proposition is built around privacy and local control: it is designed to be practical, privacy-aware, and grounded in a user's real environment, and it can be configured to operate entirely offline, removing dependence on third-party cloud services for its core functionality, which stands in contrast to mainstream voice assistants that route most or all processing through vendor cloud infrastructure. At the same time, Leon is flexible enough to integrate with both local and remote AI providers when a user does want to leverage larger cloud-hosted language models for more capable reasoning, giving users a choice between maximum privacy and maximum capability depending on their needs. Functionally, Leon supports both voice and text-based interaction: users can speak to Leon and receive spoken responses using integrated text-to-speech and speech-to-text engines, which can be configured to use either cloud-based providers or fully offline, on-device solutions, or interact via a more conventional text chat interface when voice isn't convenient. As of the most recent documentation reviewed, Leon operates through multiple distinct execution modes: a 'smart' mode that automatically selects the appropriate response strategy, a 'controlled' mode that executes deterministic, purpose-built native skills for reliable, repeatable tasks, and an 'agent' mode that performs step-by-step planning and execution for more open-ended, multi-step requests, reflecting a broader shift in the project toward agentic, tool-using AI architecture rather than simple command-and-response scripting. This is reinforced by the project's own description of itself as being 'built around tools, context, memory, and agentic execution,' and by its layered memory system, which separately tracks user preferences, ongoing daily context, and historical discussion, allowing Leon to behave more like a persistent personal assistant than a stateless chatbot. Leon's extensibility comes from its skills architecture, split into native skills (built directly into the core system for speed and reliability) and agent skills (more flexible, tool-based capabilities that can be composed dynamically), both of which developers can create and share with the broader community, and the project explicitly documents Node.js and Python bridge layers with toolkit definitions, along with Python services communicating over a TCP server, showing a deliberately polyglot architecture that lets contributors build skills in whichever language best suits the task. On the technology stack itself, Leon's codebase is roughly 68% TypeScript, 18% Python, and 10% JavaScript, with additional Sass/SCSS and HTML for its web application interface, and it requires a self-hosted server environment with Node.js 16 or higher, npm 8 or higher, Python 3.9.10, and the Pipenv dependency manager, with installation options via a CLI-based setup wizard, Docker containerization, or a fully manual install process, and support across Linux, macOS, and Windows. At the time of research, the project is undergoing a significant architectural transition, with its GitHub materials describing a '2.0 Developer Preview' phase and a version number in the 1.0.0-beta range on its stable branch, indicating Leon is still evolving rapidly toward a more mature, agent-centric rewrite rather than being a finished, static product; prospective users should expect ongoing breaking changes and active development rather than a fully polished, versioned 1.0 release. Because Leon is a community open-source project rather than a company, there is no publicly disclosed company size, headquarters, or revenue; support and roadmap direction happen through GitHub issues, community discussion, and the project's own documentation site at docs.getleon.ai. In the broader competitive landscape, Leon sits alongside other open-source or privacy-focused personal assistant and local-AI projects such as Mycroft (a now largely dormant open voice assistant), Home Assistant's Assist voice pipeline, and a growing wave of self-hosted LLM agent frameworks, while differentiating itself specifically through its long project history dating back to 2017, its dedicated voice-plus-text personal assistant framing (as opposed to a general-purpose home automation platform or a bare LLM orchestration framework), and its explicit agentic execution model that lets it plan and carry out multi-step tasks using tools rather than only answering single-turn questions, positioning Leon as a serious, privacy-respecting alternative for developers and self-hosting enthusiasts who want a customizable personal AI assistant that they fully own and control.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'c6b68bfb-e7f4-4aa7-b7c2-1fa1787822c7';

